				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/deacon-blues-117" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(630856); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=630856&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204688" alt="Deacon_Blues_117" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=630856)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/deacon-blues-117" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(630856); return false;" >Deacon_Blues_117</a></span> <span class="odate time_1291139743 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Nov 2010 17:55</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-938742">
									

<p>This is, in my not-so-frakking-humble opinion, a really good story. The tone fits in with Dr. Gears' deliberately detached personality, and helps explain how it became so.</p>
<p>I ran across a quote from an RPG the other day that reminded me of this. The character is from a fantasy RPG (either D&amp;D or GURPS Dungeon Fantasy, apparently); he's a semi-disillusioned old paladin, who's had to compromise his ideals a few times in the interests of the greater good. One piece of advice offered in-character to a new party member:</p>
<p>"To protect everyone's smiles you need to sacrifice your own. Because in the end none of this really is about what YOU want."</p>
<p>I get the feeling from this story that Gears (the character, just to be plain, not the real person) feels the same way about what the Foundation has to do.</p>

							</div>

								
					
